at|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|t|
at|
^-{ Suit preference signals }
^-|fp||cp||at|
You have come a long way in your studies of defensive signals. By now you should have a solid understanding of both attitude signals and count signals. The third (and last) type of signal that will be presented in this program is the suit preference signal. While the vast majority of the signals that you make as a defender will be either attitude or count signals, you will see that there are a few special situations where a suit preference signal can work wonders for the defense. Here is a reminder of the type of message that a suit preference signal delivers:

|
qx|4.4|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Suit preference signals are used to tell your partner that 
 you would like him to play a specific suit if he should gain the lead. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|From the above description, you may think that suit preference signals are no different from encouraging attitude signals (which can also be used to ask your partner to lead a specific suit). In a sense that is true, but there is one aspect of suit preference signals that make these signals very different from encouraging attitude signals (or any other type of signal that we have seen for that matter):

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ A suit preference signal carries a message about a suit 
 that is different from the suit in which the signal is made. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|Attitude signals encourage or discourage the suit of the signal. Count signals show an even or an odd number of cards in the suit of the signal. Suit preference signals are different - they are signals in one suit that carry a message about some other suit. |
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


tb||
nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|There are several situations where a partnership could agree to use suit preference signals on defense, but there is really only one situation where these types of signals are commonly used. Here is an example:

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|Suppose that your partner is the opening leader against a trump contract and he leads a card in a side suit that is obviously a singleton (ignore for now why this is ^*Iobvious^*N). Let's assume that your partner's opening lead is the @D3 and your diamond holding is:

|cs|3|at|^-{ |ih|pda952|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|It seems like a good idea to win your @DA |
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


at|and to lead one of your small diamonds to the next trick so that your partner can win that trick with a ruff. From a purely trick-winning point of view, it won't matter which of your spot cards you lead to the second trick so you might as well use this opportunity to give your partner some kind of signal. 

|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ One of the basic premises of signaling is that cards that are not relevant in terms of 
 winning tricks should be put to some use - the use of sending a message to your partner! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In deciding what kind of message a signal should carry in a given situation, 
 the most important question to ask is: what does your partner need to know? }
^-
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|In this particular situation, when you are about to give your partner a ruff, the most important thing you can tell him is which suit you would like him to lead back after he gets his ruff. There are several reasons why this information might be important to your partner. The main reason is that if your partner can find a way to get you back on lead, you will be able to give him a second ruff.

|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|These are the diamonds that you have left at the point where you are about to lead a diamond for your partner to ruff:
|cs|3|at|^-{ |ih|pd952|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Using suit preference signals, the diamond that you lead will tell your partner
 which suit you would like him to lead after he wins the next trick with a ruff. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a low card asks your 
 partner to lead the lower-ranking of the remaining side suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a high card asks your 
 partner to lead the higher-ranking of the remaining side suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a middle card tells your partner 
 that you have no preference as to which of the remaining side suits he leads. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Suppose that in the current example hearts is the trump suit. Here are your diamonds again:

|cs|3|at|^-{ |ih|pd952|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


at|If you lead the @D2 (your lowest diamond) to the second trick, you are sending your partner the message that you would like him to return the lower-ranking of the remaining side suits after he ruffs. The remaining side suits are spades and clubs with clubs being the lower-ranking of these 2 suits. The @D2 would ask your partner to lead a club. Perhaps you were dealt the @CA and you will be able to give your partner a second ruff if he puts you on lead with that card.

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


at|If you had the @SA instead of the @CA, you would return the @D9. The @D9, being your highest diamond, is a suit preference signal that asks your partner to lead a spade after he takes his ruff. If your partner gets the message he will put you back on lead in spades so that you can give him another diamond ruff.

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


at|Finally, if you had no high cards to speak of in either of the remaining side suits, the correct card to lead back as a suit preference signal is the @D5. The @D5, being a middle diamond, suggests that you have no strong preference between the remaining side suits. Your partner will have to use his judgment to decide on the best suit to lead back after receiving his ruff.

|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|In the diamond holding that we have been considering so far:
|n#|5|cs|3|at|^-{ |ih|pd952|at| }
^-
|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


at|you were fortunate to have been dealt diamond spot cards that look high (the @D9), |
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


at|middle (the @D5), |
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


at|and low (the @D2). |
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


at|You could use these 3 diamonds to send the exact suit preference message that you want to your partner. You can ask him to return the lower ranking side suit (clubs), |
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


at|the higher ranking side suit (spades), |
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|or you can tell him that you have no preference as to which suit he leads back after scoring his ruff.

|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ As with all types of signals, sometimes you are not dealt the ideal cards for
 giving your partner as clear a suit preference signal as you would like. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


at|You already know that the only thing you can do when you are not dealt the ideal cards for expressing the message that you would like to send to your partner is to do the best you can with what you were dealt. Hopefully your partner will consider the possibility that you may have been dealt a hand in which you did not have the card for making a signal that would be easy for him to interpret. Also, if you follow this piece of advice (which you have also seen before), your partner will have an easier time reading your signals:
|n#|7|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


cs|4|At|^-{ Always signal with the loudest card that you can afford! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|For example, sometimes you will have only 2 cards to choose from in making your suit preference signal. Since it is impossible to send 3 different messages when you have only 2 cards to play, it may be harder for your partner to understand your intended message.
|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


n#|5|cs|3|at|^-{ |ih|pd95|at| }
^-
In this example, leading back your higher diamond (the @D9) would be a suit preference signal for spades |
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


at|and leading back your lower diamond (the @D5) would be a suit preference signal for clubs. It does not matter that the @D5 is a ^*Imiddle-looking^*N spot card. What matters is that it is the lowest diamond that you have.

|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ With only 2 cards to choose from for your suit preference signal, these cards are used to 
 show preference for the highest and lowest side suits. There is no way to say "no preference". }
^-
|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


at|What if you really have no preference in a situation like this? That's just too bad. You have to go one way or the other and hope that your partner can figure out that you may not have been dealt a perfect holding to convey the message you would have liked. 

It is usually the case that you have at least ^*Isome^*N preference between the 2 remaining side suits, but if you truly have no preference you will sometimes have to guess which card to return from a holding like the one above and leave it to your partner to work things out.|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|Selecting a card to lead as a suit preference signal is not difficult from the following holdings, but as before, your partner will need to be on the ball if he is going to be able to read your signal:
|cs|3|at|^F{ |ih|pd432|at| } |n#|s|at|^Q{|ih|pd987|at| }|n^|q|at|

|at|In the first example, you have 3 diamonds to choose from. You can use these cards to ask for |
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


at|the highest suit (with the @D4), |
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


at|the lowest suit (with the @D2), |
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


at|or neither suit (with the @D3). 

|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


at|The problem is that all 3 of your diamonds might look low to your partner. Unless he is paying close attention to the other diamonds that he sees, he may read your suit preference signal as asking for the lowest side suit regardless of the diamond that you play. |
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


at|^^^^He will read the @D2 properly for sure, |
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


at|but he might not get the message if you lead back the @D4 or @D3. There is nothing you can do about this except to hope that your partner is able to see the light.

|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


at|Similarly, in the second example, all 3 of your diamonds might look high to your partner. |
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


at|If you give suit preference for the higher side suit with the @D9, the message will get through to him. |
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


at|^^^^However, it is possible that the @D8 (no preference) |
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


at|or the @D7 (preference for the lower side suit) will be difficult signals for your partner to read. |
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


at|He may well return the higher side suit regardless of the diamond that you play. 
|n#|7|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


cs|1|at|^^^-{ Don't let these examples scare you - holdings like those shown above are quite rare! }
|
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|2|at|^^
 { Historical Note } |cs|1|at|^F {  @2Attitude and count signals are older than the game of contract bridge itself. These signals were developed in the 19th century by whist players. The suit preference signal was pioneered in 1934 by Hy Lavinthal of Trenton, New Jersey. The development of suit preference signals was arguably the most important and influential development in the science of defensive play in the 20th century. }
^b@2^^
Lavinthal designed the suit preference signal specifically for the type of situation that we have been considering (as a signal to ask your partner to lead back a specific side suit after he receives a ruff). For much of the history of contract bridge, suit preference signals were used almost exclusively in this kind of situation. 

In recent years, some bridge authorities have advocated that these suit preference signals should be extended to other situations as well. It is beyond the intended scope of this program to go into a lot of detail about other situations where a partnership might choose to employ suit preference signals, but some of these situations will be mentioned here as food for thought.

|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Warning! Do not use suit preference signals in these situations unless 
 you and your partner have had a thorough discussion on these matters! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


at|Attitude and count signals as well as suit preference signals in the situation that we have seen are used by almost all serious bridge players. ^^^^The same is not true of the other forms of suit preference signals that you will soon be reading about. Do not assume that your partner is using suit preference signals in these situations!|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|at|
^-{ Some players use suit preference signals when a honor card is led in a side suit 
 against a trump contract and the dummy has a singleton or void in that suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


at|Suppose, for example, that your partner's opening lead against a trump contract is the King of a side suit and the dummy has a singleton in that suit. Your partner's lead suggests that he also holds the Queen of the suit that he led and that he does not hold the Ace of that suit. 

|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


at|At the end of the first trick, your partner will know who holds the Ace of the suit he led. Either the declarer will have won the first trick with his Ace or your partner's King will win the trick (suggesting that you have the Ace of the suit that he led). As such, there is not much point in you giving your partner an attitude signal to tell him if you have the Ace in the suit that he led - he will be finding out about the location of the Ace all by himself.

An attitude signal for the Jack of the suit that he led or a count signal (expressing if you have an even or an odd number of cards in the suit) is not likely to provide any useful information to your partner. The declarer is likely going to start ruffing his losers in the suit that was led. On many deals, the count of the suit and the location of the Jack will not be relevant to your partner.

|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ One piece of information that rates to be useful to your partner is which of the 2 
 other side suits you prefer. Suit preference signals can give him this message! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


at|The bottom line here is that the defense does not have a bright future in the suit your partner led. Suit preference signals are useful in this situation for suggesting a different suit to attack.
|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|2|at|
^-{ Some players use suit preference signals when both their
  attitude and their count in a given suit is already known. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


cs|3|at|For example, suppose that you were dealt the following holding in clubs:

|ht|e|at|^B{ |ih|pc97643|at| }

|
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


ht|g|at|
^G@2Some time during the course of the play of a deal, you discard the @C3 as a discouraging attitude signal. You will be left with these 4 cards in clubs: 
^b@2
|
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


ht|m|at|^B { |ih|pc9764|at| }

|ht|o|at|^G@2The next time you discard a club, you will be giving a remainder count signal. You would discard the @C9 to tell your partner that you had an even number of cards left in clubs. You will be left with these 3 clubs:
^b@2
|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


ht|s|at|^B  { |ih|pc764|at| }

|ht|u|n#|5|at|^G@2If you are going to discard another club, it makes a lot of sense to use that discard as a suit preference signal. The is nothing more you can tell your partner about your club holding (since he already knows your attitude and count). You might as well take advantage of this opportunity to tell him something about your holdings in the other suits.

|
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|at|
^-{ Some players use suit preference signals in the trump suit itself. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


cs|3|at|Suppose that spades are trump and that the declarer wins the first trick and starts drawing trump. This is your holding in the trump suit:
|n#|5|ht|h|at|^B{ |ih|ps863|at| }

|ht|h|n#|5|at|^G@2We have not discussed the concept of signaling in the trump suit. Most partnerships use count signals in trump, but it is common to reverse the normal meaning of count signals where the trump suit is concerned:
^b@2
|
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


cs|2|n#|5|at|
^-{ A high-low in the trump suit suggests an odd number of trumps and
 playing low-high in the trump suit suggests an even number of trumps. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


at|The theory behind this switch from the normal methodology of count signals is that you are more likely to be able to afford to part with a higher trump when you have 3 cards in the trump suit to choose from (as opposed to when you have a doubleton trump).

Giving count in the trump suit is usually not very helpful to your partner because he will quickly learn how many trumps you have when the declarer draws trump. For this reason, there is a good case for using suit preference signals in the trump suit. On most deals the most useful message you can give your partner when declarer is drawing trump is which of the side suits you like the best.|
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


