nt|^b@2^z@3You are sitting East. North, the dealer, opened the bidding with 1@H. South responded 1@S and North raised to 2@S. South jumped to 4@S which became the final contract. |
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


pc|h|at|Your partner, West, selected the @H7 as his opening lead. |
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


at|The declarer called for the @H2 from the dummy. |
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


pc|h2|at|Think about how you would defend as East. |
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3One of the first things you should consider is the heart suit. What is going on in that suit? You have 5 hearts and the dummy started with 5 cards in that suit as well. There are only 3 hearts left for the other 2 players. Your partner has played one of these hearts (the @H7). 

Only the @H3 and the @HK are unaccounted for. Furthermore, assuming your partner is using standard leads, he must have either started with the @H73 doubleton or a singleton @H7. |
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3In either case, it must be right to take your @HA. |
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


pc|hahk|at|South follows suit with the @HK so the only outstanding heart that you cannot see is the @H3. Either declarer has that card or your partner does - there is no way to know for sure. 

If your partner still has the @H3 then his lead of the @H7 (from @H73 doubleton) was in accordance with the principles of standard leads. If the declarer has the @H3, he started with @HK3 doubleton and chose to drop his @HK under your @HA.|
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Is it really possible that South played the @HK under your @HA when he did not have to? Yes. This is quite possible. In fact, if South was really dealt the @HK3 doubleton, playing the @HK to the first trick would be a very good play. For one thing, this play would leave the heart suit unblocked. More important, playing the @HK from @HK3 doubleton leaves you in doubt as to the location of the @H3. If South played the @H3 you would have no doubt about who was dealt that card!|
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Assuming that your partner and the declarer are both reasonably good players, there is strong reason to believe that the missing @H3 is in the South hand. Do you know what it is? |
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


at|Consider the fact that West led a heart. Hearts is a suit that was bid by the opponents and we have learned that it is generally a good idea to select your opening lead from one of the unbid suits. |
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3Given that North opened the bidding with 1@H, West would not have led a heart unless he had a very good reason for doing so. If your partner was dealt a singleton @H7, he would have an excellent reason for leading hearts. If he was dealt a doubleton @H73, however, the chances of a heart lead being good for the defense are not nearly as strong. It is unlikely that West would have selected a heart as his opening lead if he was dealt a doubleton in that suit. |
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
So it is reasonable to conclude that the declarer has the missing @H3 and that your partner is now void in hearts. You can lead back a heart and he will win the next trick with a ruff. All that remains is to decide which heart to return. |
pg| ***** 78 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
This is a classic situation for using suit preference signals. You know you are about to give your partner a ruff and the heart that you return can be used to tell him which of the side suits you would like him to lead back to you! |
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3If you had a preference for diamonds, the highest ranking of the remaining side suits, |
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


at|you would return your highest remaining heart (the @H8). |
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


at|If you had no strong preference between diamonds and clubs, you would return a middle heart (the @H6 or the @H5). |
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


at|On this particular hand, you have the @CK and nothing of value in diamonds. You should therefore indicate your suit preference for the lowest remaining side suit |
pg| ***** 83 ***** |


At|by leading back your lowest heart, the @H4. |
pg| ***** 84 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|pc|h4h|at|It is comforting to see South follow suit with the missing @H3, |
pg| ***** 85 ***** |


pc|sh|at|exciting to see your partner win the trick with a ruff, |
pg| ***** 86 ***** |


pc|cj|at|and positively exhilarating to see him return a club - the suit that you asked for with your suit preference signal! |
pg| ***** 87 ***** |


