^-{  Suit preference signals - Review and Exercises  }
^-|fp||at|
|cp||at|Suit preference signals are the 3rd and last major type of defensive signals that we have studied. Opportunities for using suit preference signals are rare compared to those for the other 2 types of signals (attitude and count), but as we have seen, a well-timed suit preference signal can be very helpful to the defense.

Here is a reminder of the type of message that a suit preference signal conveys:

|
pg| ***** 202 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Suit preference signals are used to tell your partner that 
 you would like him to play a specific suit if he should gain the lead. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 203 ***** |


at|Suit preference signals have an interesting property that makes them fundamentally different from both attitude signals and count signals:

|
pg| ***** 204 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ A suit preference signal carries a message about a suit 
 that is different from the suit in which the signal is made. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 205 ***** |


at|Here are some principles to keep in mind that hold true for all types of signals:

|
pg| ***** 206 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ As with all types of signals, sometimes you are not dealt the ideal cards for
 giving your partner as clear a suit preference signal as you would like. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 207 ***** |


cs|1|At|^-{ Always signal with the loudest card that you can afford! }
|
pg| ***** 208 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|The basic mechanics of suit preference signals are the same as they are for both attitude signals and count signals. High and low cards are used to carry different messages. In the case of suit preference signals, the messages carried by high and low cards are as follows:

|
pg| ***** 209 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a low card asks your 
 partner to lead the lower-ranking of the remaining side suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 210 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a high card asks your 
 partner to lead the higher-ranking of the remaining side suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 211 ***** |


cs|2|at|With suit preference signals, middle cards also carry their own messages. This is not the case with either attitude signals or count signals.

|
pg| ***** 212 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ In a suit preference situation, the play of a middle card tells your partner 
 that you have no preference as to which of the remaining side suits he leads. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 213 ***** |


at|If you are in a situation where you want to give a suit preference signal and you have only 2 cards that you can choose from, this is the principle that you should follow:

|
pg| ***** 214 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ With only 2 cards to choose from for your suit preference signal, these cards are used to 
 show preference for the highest and lowest side suits. There is no way to say "no preference". }
^-
|
pg| ***** 215 ***** |


at|There is only one situation in bridge where suit preference signals are commonly used:
|n#|7|
pg| ***** 216 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Give a suit preference signal when you lead a suit that you think your partner will ruff. }

|
pg| ***** 217 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
In recent years, some bridge authorities have advocated the use of suit preference signals in other defensive situations. There is merit to these ideas, but they are far from mainstream at this point in time. If you want to consider using suit preference signals in these situations, make sure that your partner will be on the same wavelength! 

Unless you have had prior discussion with your partner to the contrary, you should assume that suit preference signals only apply in one situation: when you lead a suit to give your partner a ruff. Here are some other situations in which it makes some sense to use suit preference:

|
