at|This last principle is arguably the most important lesson to be learned from this chapter. We have tried to categorize situations in which each of the 3 main kinds of defensive signals apply, but it is not practical to try to make rules about ^*Ievery^*N signaling situation that you might one day face as a defender. The scope of the play of the cards at bridge is simply too large.

This state of affairs is not something that you should be upset about. Indeed, the fact that you will constantly face new situations every time you play bridge is one of the reasons why the game is so challenging and stimulating. In the same way that ^*Inever^*N and ^*Ialways^*N do not really apply to principles like second hand low, third hand high, and cover an honor with an honor, making statements like "always give count in this situation" should be avoided as well.

